DR. SHERI FINK: All of the
above.

40:46.477 --> 40:50.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's -- the point of my
investigation
-- and I have been looking at
this for a few

40:50.448 --> 40:56.654 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
years -- is that it's being done
all sorts
of ways. There is no one way.
There are very

40:56.754 --> 41:03.661 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
few guidelines. Today, a group
children cancer
doctors actually published
rationing guidelines,

41:03.761 --> 41:10.635 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because children's cancer, of
all the compelling
parts of our medical system,
that has been

41:10.735 --> 41:12.737 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
hit by shortages in recent
years.

41:12.837 --> 41:16.974 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And these doctors were so
worried, and they
had so little ethical guidance,
that they

41:17.075 --> 41:21.512 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
said let's get together for a
few years, work
this through, get ethicists
involved, get

41:21.612 --> 41:27.585 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
patient representatives
involved, and come
out with some strategies for --
to offer to

41:27.685 --> 41:30.388 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
doctors who have to make these
decisions or
who may have to make them.

41:30.488 --> 41:33.358 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: One of the
quotes you have
in your stories is, "We have
been forced into

41:33.458 --> 41:36.494 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
what we think is highly an
unethical corner."

41:36.594 --> 41:40.832 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You actually profile -- one of
the characters
in your story is somebody that
is essentially

41:40.932 --> 41:46.104 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
working on inventory in the
basement of the
Cleveland hospital, and he is in
a position

41:46.204 --> 41:51.876 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to decide which one of his
clinics and which
doctors and eventually which
patients will

41:51.976 --> 41:52.877 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
get these drugs.

41:52.977 --> 41:54.779 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DR. SHERI FINK: Yes.

41:54.879 --> 41:58.516 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
That quote was from Peter
Adamson, Dr. Peter
Adamson, the Children's Ecology
Group, which

41:58.616 --> 42:04.555 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is the group that came out with
these guidelines
in "The Journal of the National
Cancer Institute."

42:04.655 --> 42:09.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the person you're speaking
about is Chris
Snyder. So, the Cleveland Clinic
has been

42:09.560 --> 42:15.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
unusually proactive. They have
hired a full-time
pharmacist pretty much just to
deal with these

42:15.500 --> 42:21.105 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
shortages in recent years. And
so Chris Snyder
is scurrying around the basement
of the Cleveland

42:21.205 --> 42:26.511 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Clinic, staying on top of these
drug shortages
and trying -- the first step, of
course, is

42:26.611 --> 42:28.379 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to conserve.

42:28.479 --> 42:32.717 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's to wipe out any waste that
you might
have in your system, and to
maximize, so that

42:32.817 --> 42:37.221 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you don't have to make those
tragic choices.
But, ultimately, sometimes, they
have had

42:37.321 --> 42:42.527 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to put restrictions on which
uses, which groups
of patients would get a drug and
which wouldn't.

42:42.627 --> 42:46.230 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, what about
the patients
in all this? You're saying that,
oftentimes,

42:46.330 --> 42:50.268 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they don't even know that the
medicine is
being rationed to or away from
them.

42:50.368 --> 42:52.136 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DR. SHERI FINK: That's right.

42:52.236 --> 42:54.906 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Sometimes, they're not being
told. A lot of
times, they're not being told.
Doctors told

42:55.006 --> 42:59.944 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
me that they don't want to worry
a patient.
There was a patient I wrote
about. Her name

43:00.044 --> 43:07.251 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is Bev. And she has Crohn's
disease, and she
relies on intravenous nutrition.
So she can't

43:07.351 --> 43:09.153 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
eat like you and I do.

43:09.253 --> 43:15.827 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And they cut -- during a
shortage period that
affected many elements of her
nutrition, she

43:15.927 --> 43:20.698 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
wasn't told. She wasn't getting
zinc and she
came up with a horrible rash,
ended up in

43:20.798 --> 43:26.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the hospital, and then found out
that this
was a classic symptom of zinc
deficiency.

43:26.237 --> 43:28.272 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And she said, why didn't anybody
tell me?

43:28.372 --> 43:33.845 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, this is just one example of
people finding
out after. There are many cases
what patients

43:33.945 --> 43:38.382 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
just aren't being told. And this
is another
ethical dimension, is, should
patients be

43:38.483 --> 43:44.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
told, at what point, and how
does the doctor
explain the relative risks of a
substitute

43:44.155 --> 43:47.558 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
drug vs. the standard drug? It's
all very
complicated.

43:47.658 --> 43:53.264 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Sheri Fink
from The New
York Times, thanks so much.

43:53.364 --> 43:59.136 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DR. SHERI FINK: Thank you.

43:59.237 --> 44:04.208 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: This week, the
government
of Denmark approved a law that
enables the

44:04.308 --> 44:09.981 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
authorities to seize valuables
from asylum
seekers in order to pay towards
their shelter

44:10.081 --> 44:11.883 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and living expenses.

44:11.983 --> 44:16.187 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's an effort to make one of
Europe's top
destinations less attractive to
refugees and

44:16.287 --> 44:22.527 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
migrants. But one of Denmark's
leading dance
troupes is taking to the stage
to expand understanding

44:22.627 --> 44:27.098 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the hardships many of those
same refugees
have faced. They're doing it by
incorporating

44:27.198 --> 44:30.935 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a number of asylum seekers into
a new ballet.

44:31.035 --> 44:34.071 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
It opens this evening in
Copenhagen's Old
Opera House.

44:34.171 --> 44:37.942 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Special correspondent Malcolm
Brabant was
at the rehearsals, and sent us
this reflection

44:38.042 --> 44:41.078 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
from the director and cast, in
their own words.

44:41.178 --> 44:50.054 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SALAM SUSU, Refugee: You cannot
explain it
in words. Like, people dying all
around you,

44:50.154 --> 45:03.034 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
friends, relatives, children,
bombs, explosions,
cars. You don't know when you're
going to

45:03.134 --> 45:07.805 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
be dead.

45:07.905 --> 45:18.549 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My name is Salam Susu. And I'm
from Syria.
I lived in Homs. I work as a
university professor

45:18.649 --> 45:25.156 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in music. I came here. I play
music. And I
work with a very high
professional people

45:25.256 --> 45:34.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who really make me feel like I'm
home. And
I really restart being a real
human being,

45:34.732 --> 45:36.634 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
feeling with everything.

45:36.734 --> 45:39.770 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRISTIAN LOLLIKE, Director: My
name is Christian
Lollike. I'm the director of
this piece called

45:39.870 --> 45:48.212 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
"Europa." It's called asylum
ballet. It's
a mix of asylum seekers and
royal ballet dancers.

45:48.312 --> 45:53.784 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm trying to sort of explode
the idea of
what is a refugee, because,,
very often in

45:53.884 --> 46:02.326 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Europe, refugees are considered
as parasites
who come to take things from us
and as a problem.

46:02.426 --> 46:06.063 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I want to show that they are
much more.

46:06.163 --> 46:14.939 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MOHAMMED AL-ISHAQ, Refugee: It
was necessary
for me to leave Pakistan because
of my sexuality.

46:15.039 --> 46:21.445 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
My name is Mohammed al-Ishaq
from Lahore,
Punjab.

46:21.545 --> 46:26.651 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was becoming hard for me to
survive and
it was becoming extremely hard
for my parents

46:26.751 --> 46:33.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to survive because of me also,
because they
also started getting threats
from the religious

46:33.157 --> 46:39.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
authorities who gave me threats
also that,
either I become non-gay, like
non-homosexual,

46:39.697 --> 46:46.704 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and get married normally to a
woman, or I
find my own ways, or be ready to
be killed.

46:46.804 --> 46:55.880 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELIAN YAAKOB DAWOOD, Refugee:
When the bombs
came, we were hoping they would
hit our neighbor,

46:55.980 --> 46:57.782 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
not us.

46:57.882 --> 47:12.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My name is Elian Yaakob Dawood.
I came from
Syria. And now I'm here in
Denmark. I need

47:12.596 --> 47:21.739 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to send a message. We all send a
message.
We are good. We love the life,
not everybody

47:21.839 --> 47:24.575 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a religious fanatic.

47:24.675 --> 47:33.684 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRISTIAN LOLLIKE: I think it's
actually scary
and wrong that the Danish
government is trying

47:33.784 --> 47:40.424 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to scare people away, instead of
being constructive
and work together in the
European Union and

47:40.524 --> 47:43.861 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to create a solution on this
problem.

47:43.961 --> 47:50.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's very important, especially
in Denmark,
where a lot of people are afraid
of asylum

47:50.267 --> 47:55.139 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
seekers and refugees. I think
it's very important
to see that they are human
beings and they

47:55.239 --> 47:57.508 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have all kind of skills and
qualifications.

47:57.608 --> 48:02.546 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SALAM SUSU: They are not all
similar. There
are a lot of really
high-educated people who

48:02.646 --> 48:06.984 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
run away from death to rebuild
their life,
and to integrate into the
society, to live

48:07.084 --> 48:14.592 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the life that they really
wanted, and to explain
that we are good enough to be in
your society.

48:14.692 --> 48:19.230 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MOHAMMED AL-ISHAQ: This will
help people in
thinking differently for
refugees. They look

48:19.330 --> 48:22.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
at us as normal human beings,
the way we are,
not just the parasite.

48:22.933 --> 48:28.939 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As far as I'm concerned, it's
very self-therapeutic
for me. Speaking about my own
life, it gives

48:29.039 --> 48:38.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
me a feeling that, when I tell
people my story,
people respond in a way that is
not confrontation

48:38.115 --> 48:39.950 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
or condemnation.

48:40.050 --> 48:46.090 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm not scared that they're
going to punish
me. It's not about the people
who come from

48:46.190 --> 48:52.963 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
war-trodden countries only. It's
not just
the war that people are dying
of. There are

48:53.063 --> 48:58.602 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
other reasons also. And I do not
come from
a place where there is war going
on. But there

48:58.702 --> 49:02.673 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is a war going on at a society
level for me,
for my sake.

49:02.773 --> 49:08.078 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I'm sure there are people
who have other
reasons, other than war or even
sexuality,

49:08.179 --> 49:11.515 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that they do not find a place to
survive where
they are.

49:11.615 --> 49:20.324 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SALAM SUSU: We got asylum today.
The papers
and the commune, and -- yes, I
can't explain

49:20.424 --> 49:27.131 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
too much, because it's so good.
Like, you
had a paper, you are not nobody
anymore. You

49:27.231 --> 49:29.667 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
became a human being.

49:29.767 --> 49:40.311 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My dream? To have a life again.
To live. To
experience my humanity. It's
really incredible.

49:40.411 --> 49:48.419 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I really start to experience my
skills on
a real world, among the real
people, who really

49:48.519 --> 50:03.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
start to know who I am. I'm like
stepping
on stairs to dream.

50:03.400 --> 50:18.082 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Finally
